annotation.TEXT: Until I see any actual changes, I will make this run more challenging by skipping some items, but I'm not going to go totally swordless.
Alright, that'll do for now. Okay, so I can only exit this screen to the west, and I bet that'll take me to the graveyard screen with four Green Moblins.
I guess I'll get these 30 rupees, which I initially missed the first time around.
Pfft... Now I get a fairy, after I don't need it anymore.
Blaster combo! (9 kills)
I'm also going to skip the heart container in the SE corner of the overworld as well for the time being.
Well, this'll only be useful if I decide to go shopping. However, I think I'm going to skip the shops for now.
Fairy count: 7
Hello, and welcome back to Zelda - Another Evil! Now, I've gone and searched every possibly bombable or walk-through-able wall so far, but found nothing.
Hah, I remembered you this time, Leever!
Here are some Zols that aren't glitchy-looking. And, since I can deal at least 2 damage with my attacks now, I can kill them without them splitting into Gels.
I don't know if there'll actually be anything changed in the second quest in this hack, but I'll take a look anyway.
Nope, you're still the same, and unfortunately, I can't obtain the boat this time.
NOTICE: I've removed the content ID matched audio from this point to about 2:25.
Whoa, geez! There's another Orange Wizrobe, and two Blue Wizrobes! Blue Wizrobes have 9 HP, and if you collide with them or get hit by their magic, you'll lose 2 hearts.
Umm... Hey, wake up and tell me to obtain the key already!

Yep, just like that. Actually, the game only checks to see if the first five characters of your name say "ZELDA", so you can type whatever you like for the remaining three characters, such as your initials if you want.
Yep.
DOUBLE KILL!
Hmm... I probably should've sped up some of the footage here. Oh, well.

Unfortunately, your current life gets set to 3 hearts whenever you do that, but that's okay. I'm sure I can find some hearts or a fairy at some point. Now, over here is a screen that I somehow never visited before.
Alright, so will level 1 be any different?
So, there's yet another locked door. It's nice to see that this dungeon is bigger and more complex than the previous ones.
Alright, I've arrived back at the entrance to level 9. That didn't take too long.
Does this tree stump still contain a helpful Moblin that gives me 30 rupees?

In the original Zelda, the Magic Wand is effective against them as well, especially with the Magic Book, since the resulting flames will deal additional damage as they run through them. Too bad this hack doesn't seem to give you those items.
Yep, "ZELDASRA" works just fine. Alright, I'll just get rid of these two files that I just created now...
New enemy: Fire. It's totally stationary, is destroyed with one hit from your sword, and deals half a heart of damage if you foolishly run into it.

Well, let's check it out. When you're on the second quest, there will be a sword icon right next to Link on your file. Also, you can jump straight to the second quest on a new game by entering your name as "ZELDA".
Let's do a King combo here and hopefully get at least one more heart...
So, should I check out level 9 first, or level 5 first?
Wow, my reward for beating them was a heart container. I guess that could qualify as a boss/mini-boss battle, perhaps. They're more of a boss than 8 Stalfos, at least.
Okay, let's see what's in this room up here now.
King combo!
With the Magic Sword, each Lanmola takes a total of 5 hits to defeat. Being at full life so that you can shoot sword beams gives you a big advantage against them.
Bah, forgot about that Leever!
Alright, so what's level 5 like?
Wow, I'm sucking all of a sudden! The "critical annoyance" alarm is going off, and if I let these guys hit me one more time, I'm finished!
Gah, darned Leever!
Whoa, this is different! Umm...
Now, I could go west, but I want to see what's behind this locked door down here first.
(Aw, I should've ended the episode here and had you guys vote, but I didn't think of that while playing. Oh, well.)

So, I guess that's it. This dungeon had a total of eight rooms (with the 8th one not properly showing up on the map for some reason). It was larger and tougher than the previous dungeons, but it was still on the short side.
Ooh, more money, which would've been more useful near the start of the game, but I probably don't need it now. Thanks anyway, though.
Okay, I was going to leave this Ghini alone, but it annoyed me a bit with the way it moved in my way there.
BGM: Super Marisa Land - Underground Stage
Awesome combo! (8 kills)
Okay, so I don't think the second quest has a proper level 1. Instead, it just consists of a single room with an Old Man tip from the original Zelda's level 1 in the first quest.
Oh, maybe I should check out these caves along the way, to see if they happen to contain anything different in the second quest.
Alright, back to full life.

Oh, cool! It's this shop! I didn't think I'd be able to get these things since I didn't have the boat needed to reach the other location of this shop. And, I have enough money to buy everything! Huzzah!

Whoa, Red Lanmolas. Okay, be careful, since getting hit by them costs you 2 of your hearts. As you attack them, they lose segments from their bodies until only their heads remain, at which point you can finish them off. I think each segment has 4 HP, but I'm not 100% sure about that.
You know what? I'd better buy a heart as well so that I'm not at death's door, and to stop that beeping, which I'm sure is getting annoying to some of you guys.
I really wish I had a candle so that I could check the SW green tree here...
Cool, I'm back to full health. Oh, and I'm having the fairy and pointless clock counters carry over from the first quest.
Epilepsy warning: The screen is going to rapidly flash for a few seconds. So, you may want to look away until music starts playing.
Okay, so I need another key, and it's obvious that there's something special about the west wall here, but I can't walk through it, so that just leaves one thing left to try... Bombs!
I could drink my potion, but I'm confident that I can avoid getting hit here again.
Good thing this room didn't have a half-dozen Blue Wizrobes in it!
Yeah, slaying any one of the initial Ghinis destroys all of the invincible Ghinis. And, I can do that up to four times on this screen.

Secondly, we have Like Likes. They have 9 HP, and if they hit you, you'll take a full heart of damage and be eaten! If you get eaten, you can break free by swinging your sword to kill it from within, but if you had the Magic Shield, it'll be gone.
DOUBLE KILL!
Yeah, doing that brings up this menu, but it doesn't count as a death. By doing this, I can quickly return to where I started the game.
Fairy count: 8
Oof! My goal is to gain hearts, not lose them! Don't get sloppy now! ...Also, I think I'm going to speed up some of this footage.
Oh, while I'm here, I'm going to check something...
I got a nice amount of cash from those "money spiders".
Ah, there we go. I was looking for hearts. Okay, I'm going to move on now.

However, I also looked over the entire overworld again, and while doing so, I discovered something I missed, and it's right near the start of the game. So, if I press up and A on controller 2 while this subscreen is open...
Just 12 rupees and nothing else.
DOUBLE KILL!
BTW, Like Likes never drop any items for some reason.
Yep, I needed a bomb there. And, I think I can only get them as random drops from certain enemies in this hack, since no shops sell them, and they weren't a "room drop", so to speak.

And, I do believe that's the only thing I missed. As I said, I already checked all of the walls in the dungeons to see if any could be bombed or walked through. And, I even checked every possibly bombable spot on the overworld, and found nothing. So, I guess I'll start heading back to level 9 now.
Unfortunately, this means that I can't get the boat from level 1, which makes level 2 inaccessible. However, I can still reach level 5 and level 9.
And, let's begin the second quest now!
Click! There goes the key I got from level 2.
Yay, I beat the game!

Well, this episode has gone on plenty long enough, so I'm going to save all that for next time! This dungeon will probably be a bit challenging with my current status, but I'm certainly game! To be continued... Yo!
Oh, I have to remember that I can't one-shot Zora right now.
Alright, let's head towards the graveyard area now, which I fortunately don't need a boat to reach.
For whatever reason, I simply never entered this screen, which has a waterfall, and just like in the original Zelda 1, you can walk into the waterfall to find a hidden cave.
And let's watch the credits roll... (Even though they're just the same credits from the original game.)

Thank you! I don't know why the cave NPCs sometimes take several seconds to materialize like that. I've occasionally seen that happen to enemies as well, and you can't interact with them until they come out of their "cloud".

The Orange Wizrobes aren't usually too difficult to avoid and are fairly slow with their attacks, but the Blue Wizrobes have a lot more HP, move erratically, and launch rapid-fire magic when they're lined up with you horizontally or vertically.
Alright, let's do this!

Alright, I think I will go shopping now, and also get that SE heart container, because I have no idea what to expect in levels 5 and 9. The game might throw a room containing half a dozen Blue Wizrobes at me for all I know!
Yeah, can't go north from there. Hey, maybe I'll get lucky and be able to get a boat from level 5 or level 9 somehow.

New enemy: Old Man. Totally invincible, even though you can hit him. Hitting him even once prompts him to start shooting fireballs at you from the flames until you leave the room. (NOTE: This only happens in dungeons.)
Now, it is true that the Blue Wizrobes' magic is weaker than the magic of the Orange Wizrobes, but they are still way more dangerous.
Whoa. Okay, there's two new enemies here. First, there's the Traps in the corners, which are invincible, and deal a full heart of damage if they hit you.
Okay, good enough. Let's see what's in this cave.
Ah, yes. There is still the second quest. I wonder if it'll be any different from the first quest in this hack, though...
Wait, what?! My reward for clearing this room is the Triforce that Ganon leaves behind after you defeat him in the original Zelda?! So, were those Wizrobes the final boss?!
Oh, right. I don't have the Magic Shield. I gotta remember these things!

Okay, I think I know what the deal is here. I'm on the exact screen where level 3 would be in the first quest of the original Zelda. However, this screen is one of the few overworld screens that changes in the second quest, and I guess this hack didn't take that into account.
Also, just so you know, your sword and bombs are the only things that'll work on Wizrobes. No other weapons will do anything to them.
No "room drop" here, so I guess I'll have to get the key from elsewhere.
This probably won't take too long.

Actually, it takes them a second to fully digest your Magic Shield, so if you break free really quickly (if it was like one hit away from dying), or you quickly open the subscreen and press up+A on controller 2 to bring up the save menu, you might be able to save your shield.
Yep, and I'm fortunately not hopelessly embedded in the wall.

...Level 4?! ...Oh, this could be the original Zelda's second quest level 4, since this hack seems to have not taken the second quest into account! If that's the case, then I can get a raft (boat) here, which'll let me access level 2!

Oh, man! Orange Wizrobes! Be very careful! They have 4 HP, so one Magic Sword hit or bomb will defeat them. But, colliding with them deals 1 heart of damage, and getting hit by their magic deals a whopping 4 hearts of damage! Avoid their magic at all costs, or block it with the Magic Shield!
